what to wear to dinner and how to get a ride home from a friend’s house. The bombings and rockets were used like black comedy, particularly as the politicians in Israel kept waffling about what to do.

The Palestinians framed the uprising in terms that Israelis understood: they didn’t need to bomb a military installation to justify retaliatory strikes, like the aircraft that peppered downtown Gaza with much deadly fire, or tearcyclines, which leak a lethal gas. That’s way more complicated.

The Palestinians watched from Gaza as tanks rolled over southern Israel and teargased our cities. Gaza itself saw much of its coastline and territory devastated by Israeli retributive strikes, setting off the familiar clamour for weapons to blow back at them. Righteous Israeli indignation at being provoked does not go down well here, but riots work pretty well to appease domestic audiences. And so, on cue, Palestinians rose up on government buildings and beat each other with rocks, while armed women joined with men in beating up hummus-serving counter-protestors.

It was a street fight, as it always is when there are no more boundaries.

At the moment I write this, 150 people, including some children and many total innocents in the wrong place at the wrong time, have been killed in Israel alone. I fear for civilians the world over.

Wednesday, 11 March 2009

On A Secure Element (Via @TEDTalks Haifa, Israel)

Neta Cohen
